Hurricane season officially begins June 1st. Its most active period
usually begins Aug.  1st.  In the last 40 years there have been an
average of six hurricanes per year.  Drought in West Africa was
responsible for a drop in Atlantic hurricanes in the 1970s and 1980s.
The drought robbed storm systems of moisture needed to start their
escalation into hurricanes.  In five of the last six hurricane seasons
there have been just two to five hurricanes each year, except for the
seven in 1985. There were five hurricanes in 1984, four in 1986, and
three in 1987.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d34"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880601-0040"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="H">  

Typically, Atlantic hurricane season is June 1-Nov 30, with six of 10
named tropical storms becoming hurricanes with drenching rain and wind
over 74 mph. 1987 had three hurricanes and four tropical
storms. Hurricane Emily, the fastest moving hurricane in this century,
hit the Dominican Republic on September 22nd with wind gusts up to 110
mph, killing three. It recovered enough to belt Bermuda with 116 mph
winds three days later.  Hurricane Arlene meandered through the
Atlantic in mid-August with top winds of 75 mph. Hurricane Floyd hit
Key West with 75 mph winds but fizzled out over the Everglades and
Miami in mid-October.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d34"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880913-0204"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="H">  

Hurricane Gilbert, sprawled across the western Caribbean, gained
hurricane-force winds over the weekend and became a Category 5 storm
Tuesday afternoon with winds of 160 mph and central pressure of 26.66
inches. It should reach the Gulf of Mexico by Thursday. It is one of
the Great Hurricanes as far as intensity, size and destructive
potential. Category 5 storms making landfall this century have been
the 1935 hurricane that struck the Florida Keys and killed 600; and
1969's Hurricane Camille, which devastated the Mississippi coast,
killing 256. The last major hurricane to make landfall was Elena in
1985 along the Mississippi, Alabama and Florida Panhandle.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d34"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880914-0079"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="H">  

The barometric pressure at Hurricane Gilbert's center plummeted to
26.13 inches at 5:58pm Tuesday night, making it the most intense
hurricane ever recorded in the Western Hemisphere from that
standpoint. Gilbert gained hurricane-force winds last weekend and by
Tuesday night became a Category 5 storm with winds of 175 mph. The two
other Category 5 storms to hit land this century were the Labor Day
hurricane of 1935, which struck the Florida Keys and killed 408; and
1969's Hurricane Camille, which devastated the Mississippi coast,
killing 256. The last major hurricane to make landfall was Elena in
1985 along the Mississippi, Alabama and Florida Panhandle.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d34"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP880914-0027"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="H">  

Hurricane Gilbert, barreling toward Mexico's Yucatan Peninsula, has 75
mph winds and a record 26.13 barometric pressure. With tropical storm
force winds extending 250 miles north and 200 miles south, it is twice
the size of last month's Debby, barely reaching 74 mph. Other Category
5 storms were the 1935 Labor Day hurricane, with winds above 150 mph
and a low pressure of 26.35; and 1969's Camille with 172 mph winds and
a 25-foot high storm surge, leaving $1.4 billion in damage. Gilbert's
surge is forecast as 8-12 feet.  A Sept. 8th, 1900 hurricane hit
Galveston and killed over 6,000, the worst US natural disaster.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d34"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP881018-0136"
