SUMMARIZER="H">  

Hurricane Joan's winds slowly grew to 80 mph as it skimmed Colombia's
coast on an unusual southern path. Originally expected to weaken, it
reached hurricane force Monday night.  In Colombia it left 50 dead or
missing and triggered flooding. At noon today its center was 70 miles
offshore, 380 miles east of the Island of San Andres, moving at 10 mph
and kept on course by a strong high-pressure system over the northern
Caribbean.  Last month Hurricane Gilbert left more than 300 dead and
caused billions of dollars damage as it tore through Jamaica, the
Cayman Islands, and the Yucatan peninsula.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d34"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="AP890529-0030"
SELECTOR="F"
SUMMARIZER="H">  

In 1960 Hurricane Donna struck the Florida Keys at Marathon, then
raked across Naples and Fort Myers before weakening inland. Last
season, Atlantic hurricanes killed 505 people. Gilbert killed more
than 300 and did heavy damage in Mexico, Jamaica, Haiti and the
Dominican Republic as it blasted across the western Caribbean and part
of the Gulf of Mexico, including the Florida Keys, the Florida Straits
and Cuba. Joan hovered off the coast of Central America for days
before howling in with top winds of 135 mph.  Joan caused mudslides,
floods and other damage in Nicaragua, Costa Rica, Colombia and
Panama.</SUM>

<SUM
DOCSET="d34"
TYPE="PERDOC"
SIZE="100"
DOCREF="LA080189-0042"
